Press Release

March 22, 2012
By OccupyStLouis

March 22–Last Thursday, March 15, attendees of the Occupy Midwest Conference were peacefully complying with police orders to vacate Compton Hill Reservoir Park, when they were violently attacked by St. Louis City police officers. The Occupy Movement is a collective response to social injustice and corporate greed. Rather than addressing the ongoing crisis of families being foreclosed on and the resulting destabilization of neighborhoods, a high unemployment rate, and the corporate syphoning of money from public education, the city of St. Louis is using it’s resources to repress a non-violent assembly.

“We felt very safe in the park until the police showed up. As we were crossing the street to leave, a line of blue charged into the crowd – batons swinging – and began striking people. It was chaos. The screams of those being beaten were terrifying to hear. I felt helpless,” reports Carrie Bumgardner Luna.

Despite the fact that he was not resisting arrest, one Occupier was repeatedly beaten in the face with the butt of a mag-lite. After already being beaten and cuffed, an officer then methodically snapped and broke two of his fingers. Another Occupier was repeatedly beaten in the head requiring staples. Both Occupiers were hospitalized. A third Occupier was hit in the neck and choked with a baton, thrown to the ground and kicked in the face causing permanent damage to his jaw structure.

“It’s shocking and disheartening to see people you love being violently attacked, bleeding from their bruised faces. It was a senseless betrayal of trust. It really helps me better understand what people of color in our city go through every day,” said Oren Goldberg.

Occupy St. Louis has always been responsible stewards of public space and disavow the graffiti damage done to the Compton Hill Reservoir Park.

###

Comments are closed.

  • Events on August 4, 2012
    • Reclaim St. Louis - The McMillan Project
      Starts: 10:00 am
      Ends: August 5, 2012 - 1:00 pm
      Location: 4716 McMillan
      Description: Reclaim St Louis will be meeting at 4716 McMillan this Saturday morning from 10am-1pm. We will be doing work on the inside and outside of the property.

      Check the Reclaim St. Louis page for specifics on how far along the project has come and what we might need to the work day.

      The McMillan Project is a total rehab of a run down property to be turned over to the neighborhood. This space will used by the community for their needs, as they see appropriate. This is the first of community rehab programs the Reclaim is instituting.

      Reclaim St Louis is a diverse network of people, groups, and organizations that seek to create radical change in the way our society functions. We want to live in a society that prioritizes people and communities, love and education, acceptance and justice, and that decries oppression. We directly confront and fight against people, groups and organizations that oppress us while simultaneously creating new ways of living, interacting, and developing a reality which coincides with our beliefs. Our focus is on grassroots organizing and community building through work in such areas as housing, food gardens, alternative energy, bartering, education, leadership training, and justice.

      Location: Occupy the Midwest Conference: Detroit
      Description: The 2nd ever Occupy The Midwest Conference is coming to Detroit this summer for 4 days of regional coordination, direct action planning, and community building.

      The theme for this conference will be “Another World is Possible” which will showcase YOUR ideas aimed to improve the world, better communities and inspire initiative from citizens around the world. The failure of outdated systems has led to a new demand for new and improved ones that meet not only the financial requirements, but the environmental, ethical, physical and mental health requirements as well. Meet us in Detroit for organizational meetings meant to help cities better coordinate with one another, thought provoking teach-ins, fun, entertainment, and opportunities to share our visions for a better world.

      Reclaim St Louis is a diverse network of people, groups, and organizations that seek to create radical change in the way our society functions. We want to live in a society that prioritizes people and communities, love and education, acceptance and justice, and that decries oppression. We directly confront and fight against people, groups and organizations that oppress us while simultaneously creating new ways of living, interacting, and developing a reality which coincides with our beliefs. Our focus is on grassroots organizing and community building through work in such areas as housing, food gardens, alternative energy, bartering, education, leadership training, and justice.
